provides a detailed account of the operation and effectiveness of these new forms of federalism in order to address a central question: Have co-management boards been successful in ensuring substantial Indigenous involvement in policies affecting the land and wildlife in their traditional territories? Graham White tackles this question, drawing on decades of research and writing about the politics of Northern Canada. He begins with an overview of the boards, examining their legal foundations, structure and membership, decision-making processes, and independence from government. He then presents case studies of several important boards. While White identifies constraints on the role Northern Indigenous peoples play in board processes, he finds that overall they exercise extensive decision-making influence. These findings are provocative and offer valuable insights into our understanding of the importance of land claims boards and the role they play in the evolution of treaty federalism in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAdvisory boardszCanada, NorthernvCase studies. 0aAdvisory boardszCanada, Northern. 0aCommunity-based conservationzCanada, NorthernvCase studies. 0aConservation leadershipzCanada, NorthernvCase studies. 0aConservation of natural resourceszCanada, NorthernvCase studies. 0aEnvironmental policyzCanada, Northern. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanada, NorthernxClaims. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanada, NorthernxGovernment relations. 0aWildlife managementxGovernment policyzCanada, Northern. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Environmental Policy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311127253508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020z978311127473708iTitle is part of eBook package:dD